WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Hi everyone, thank you for sticking around to the last talk here.

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:22.799
My name is Tran, and this is me two years ago, fresh out of academia, pre-pregnancy.

00:00:22.799 --> 00:00:27.240
This was the day before I started my job at Bristol Myers Squibb.

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:30.080
Very excited, as you can see.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:37.320
Now, like with many new jobs, my first weeks were filled with training and orientations

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:45.279
and getting to know my new co-workers, familiarizing myself with everything else in the organization,

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:49.439
which left me feel like this a few weeks later.

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:54.240
I still remember the moment when I first learned to ski, and I felt like I started to get the

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:55.240
hang of it.

00:00:55.240 --> 00:01:01.439
I felt confident, I'm on a nicely groomed trail, I can turn my weight forward, feeling

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:02.520
very good.

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:03.919
But then comes a powder day.

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:07.199
Now, if you ski, you know what happens.

00:01:07.199 --> 00:01:08.199
Everything falls apart.

00:01:08.199 --> 00:01:15.080
I am no longer in control, I cannot turn, there's way too much powder, and I was scared.

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:19.720
I felt like I wasn't good enough, and there was still a lot more to learn.

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:26.959
Well, at BMS, I started my hands on like a few different bigger projects, and I had very

00:01:26.959 --> 00:01:28.360
little contacts on them.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:35.080
Most of my time was spent digging around for essentially non-existent documentation, and

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:40.639
any progress at that point felt extremely incremental.

00:01:40.639 --> 00:01:46.279
But in retrospect, I think the onboarding process can be structured quite in a straightforward

00:01:46.279 --> 00:01:50.080
way with three items on the checklist.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:54.480
You want to understand the company systems, where the servers are and everything.

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:58.720
You want to build relationships with your new colleagues, and I do think that you also

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:06.559
want to develop some new skills and start to contribute.

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:14.199
So like Lydia's journey of learning data science, how she structured that around R4DS, my argument

00:02:14.199 --> 00:02:19.639
today is that by structuring the onboarding process around a small doable problem, you'll

00:02:19.639 --> 00:02:23.759
be able to check off all of these items on your list.

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:28.720
Lucky for me, this problem came very quickly after I joined.

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:34.600
So we were in a bigger brainstorming meeting when my manager, Ian, sent this message on

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:35.600
Teams.

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:37.360
Do we have a BMS color theme?

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:39.199
Would be very useful.

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:43.479
So I thought, well, I can continue to get frustrated and struggle with these two bigger

00:02:43.479 --> 00:02:51.080
projects or I can take on a new one that is more fun and hopefully more doable.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:57.000
And today, I'm here to tell you the story, what I learned in building this package that

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:03.039
I later named BMS Dash and how rewarding it felt and the environment, the very engaging

00:03:03.039 --> 00:03:06.919
and productive environment that it created.

00:03:06.919 --> 00:03:09.880
So first, the questions.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:13.000
Before you build anything, you're always faced with tons of questions.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.279
Mine was, where can I find the color templates?

00:03:17.279 --> 00:03:19.240
What about the fonts?

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:23.279
What are these .WORF2 and TTF files?

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:25.639
I've never seen them before.

00:03:25.639 --> 00:03:26.639
How does Shiny work?

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:31.440
I've never built a Shiny app before, although many people in my team have.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:34.960
And then once I get something, then where do I host the app?

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:40.440
And I've heard about this BSLib package that's very good for theming.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:43.320
Will it be useful?

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:49.720
And is there a way to circumvent the manual installation of fonts on the user's computer?

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:54.960
And finally, once I have this package together, how do I distribute?

00:03:54.960 --> 00:04:01.039
At first, I was trying to work through all these questions by myself, doing my own research

00:04:01.039 --> 00:04:06.160
and everything, but I soon realized that these questions were a great excuse to talk to my

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:07.919
incredible new colleagues.

00:04:07.919 --> 00:04:16.320
So let me introduce you to my co-author of VMS Dash, Leslie, Clara, Lon, and Ian.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:22.899
These individuals have been incredibly welcoming and supporting to me from the beginning.

00:04:22.899 --> 00:04:28.359
When I first joined, they would answer every single question I had from, oh, where is the

00:04:28.359 --> 00:04:30.000
branding information store?

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.799
Or how do I ignore this file when I deploy my Shiny app?

00:04:35.799 --> 00:04:40.279
And also, these questions, so instead of one-on-ones, instead of going through these

00:04:40.279 --> 00:04:42.880
small talks and ask about, oh, how was your day?

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:44.600
What did you do during the weekend?

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:53.160
I had these real questions that they can answer, and they were great starting points for conversations.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:58.239
I was surprised to learn that at VMS, we actually used a lot of Posit products before it was

00:04:58.239 --> 00:05:00.239
called Posit Team.

00:05:00.239 --> 00:05:08.480
So for VMS Dash, I would develop the package on Workbench, deploy some of the example Shiny

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:15.200
apps and Flex dashboards and notebooks on Connect, and then finally, once I had the

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:22.119
package, I could distribute it on, I could put it on Package Manager so that other people

00:05:22.119 --> 00:05:26.880
in my team and the company can download and use it.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:31.359
I also learned about the JIRA Ticket System, Confluence Pages, and how to set proxy when

00:05:31.359 --> 00:05:40.359
I'm on VPN so that I can download the R packages from Crayon, because somehow VMS blocked that.

00:05:40.359 --> 00:05:44.239
What new R skills have I learned?

00:05:44.239 --> 00:05:46.640
I learned that bslib is magical.

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:52.880
I don't know if many of you here have used it, but it's great for Shiny, and especially

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:59.359
in my case, on the theming side, if you've seen BS stands for Bootstrap.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:05.519
If you've used this function BS Theme Preview, what it will do is spin up an example dashboard

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:06.519
for you.

00:06:06.519 --> 00:06:12.640
In here, you can choose what theme you like, the colors, the fonts, and once you're done

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:19.000
with all of that, all you need to do is close the app, and what bslib would give you is

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:24.359
this snippet of code that you can basically copy and paste into your theme argument in

00:06:24.359 --> 00:06:29.700
your Shiny function, so incredibly helpful if you haven't checked it out, I highly recommend

00:06:29.700 --> 00:06:31.399
you do so.

00:06:31.399 --> 00:06:32.559
So that's basically what I did.

00:06:32.559 --> 00:06:39.640
I just wrapped it around a function I called BMS Light, and then put those color hex codes

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:45.720
into my default argument, and then called BS Theme in my function.

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:47.239
What about the dot, dot, dots?

00:06:47.239 --> 00:06:53.000
So the rest of this function was to do fonts.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:58.200
Initially, it was really hard to kind of figure out all these font things, and the user would

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:02.679
have to install the font and load it into R manually.

00:07:02.679 --> 00:07:10.399
What I did was digging around the bslib GitHub issues and found this really nice issue, and

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:16.000
I said it's really nice because the poster had created an excellent reproducible example

00:07:16.079 --> 00:07:22.279
where I found this one line that was helpful in my case.

00:07:22.279 --> 00:07:26.839
They said, oh, this line borrows the font from bslib, so then I learned that, oh, I

00:07:26.839 --> 00:07:32.399
just need to put these wolf2 font files that I found earlier in the branding information

00:07:32.399 --> 00:07:39.359
into my inst directory in the package, and then use this function, add resource path

00:07:39.359 --> 00:07:42.000
in my package.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So that's what I did.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:49.200
Put it into unload, and finally, another tidbit here is that you have to use this font,

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:55.600
the package, to add the font into your environment, so in this case, the font that we have is

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:57.600
BMS Humanity.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:59.279
All right.

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:04.880
So with all of that together, now all the user have to do is to change theme equals

00:08:04.880 --> 00:08:09.600
BMS Light, and then you would get an app that looks something like this.

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:16.279
You would have the BMS signature, Passion Popal, and also our BMS Humanity font, and

00:08:16.279 --> 00:08:22.959
I couldn't capture the entire screenshot here for obvious reasons, but hopefully you can

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:26.239
have a feel of what it looks like.

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:31.880
I also added a few different functions for ggplot theming.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:37.440
So for example, this is an example plot using the default theme, but once you add scale

00:08:37.479 --> 00:08:43.400
fill BMS and theme BMS, it would change the color to use our own colors, the BMS colors,

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:47.599
and then using the Humanity font again.

00:08:47.599 --> 00:08:50.799
I learned, so this function is show BMS colors.

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:52.440
I find it incredibly helpful.

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:57.599
I sort of stole this from my friend Jake Riley at the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia

00:08:57.599 --> 00:09:04.039
when I saw his talk, but yeah, just a great, he's done something, internal package for

00:09:04.039 --> 00:09:05.039
CHOP as well.

00:09:05.039 --> 00:09:09.760
But I think this is a great way to show, especially with the new RStudio IDE, you can see all

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:14.799
the colors and everything, so that the user can kind of pick which colors they want, and

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:21.440
they don't have to go dig deep into any documentation for, you know, oh, what colors should I use

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:25.400
if I want this to be kind of looking like BMS brand.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:26.479
Okay.

00:09:26.479 --> 00:09:30.960
One last tip on BSLib.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:36.679
So with all of that, your DD data table, if you use it in your app, which we do a lot

00:09:36.679 --> 00:09:42.719
in our organization, it may still have this default blue when you select a row, and if

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:47.440
you're like me, that's really annoying, like this blue in the middle of all the purple.

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:52.559
So to change this color, however, you can use BS add rules to add a little bit more

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:55.280
sass into your app.

00:09:55.280 --> 00:10:01.359
So this just speaks to kind of how customizable BSLib is.

00:10:01.359 --> 00:10:05.239
And finally, just a warning, is to watch out for different bootstrap versions.

00:10:05.239 --> 00:10:09.159
So make sure to kind of, you know, try to pass through that version argument, because

00:10:09.159 --> 00:10:15.039
you may have a different shiny app and different, with different versions.

00:10:15.039 --> 00:10:18.840
So if the user wants to use a different version, they can do so.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:20.119
All right.

00:10:20.119 --> 00:10:21.479
So I'm now happy.

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:26.159
I think all of my skills have kind of improved a little bit in R, but also some of my new

00:10:26.159 --> 00:10:30.719
relationships, I've gotten a handle of, I've gotten some understanding of the company's

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:31.719
internal systems.

00:10:31.719 --> 00:10:36.960
There was still a lot more to learn, but I was happy to know that, you know, the package

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:40.320
was used right away, and it's still being heavily used today.

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:44.280
Very exciting to see, you know, any app, any new app that comes out that have this, you

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:48.039
know, BMS dash theme.

00:10:48.039 --> 00:10:53.080
I'm a huge fan of packages, because of all of these advantages that it gives you, you

00:10:53.080 --> 00:11:00.440
can read more on about, you know, advantages of internal packages in this amazing blog

00:11:00.440 --> 00:11:02.840
post by Emily Reeder.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:10.280
Some of the ideas for creating, like, starter packages, if you're a new hire, is to get

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:16.760
your package to connect to databases, or perform some simple imputation missing values, of

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:22.559
imputation of missing values, or common visualizations or data aggregations.

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:25.760
But it doesn't have to be a package.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:29.919
If you're a new hire, you can just add more to the documentation, or if the documentation

00:11:29.919 --> 00:11:36.719
doesn't exist, create Wasm, put it in a notebook, deploy it on connect, make it visible for

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:38.239
other people to use.

00:11:38.239 --> 00:11:46.239
You can create setup guide, how to set up your VS code to work with R in this EC2 instance.

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:48.479
Or you can make benchmarks.

00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:57.080
So this is an example notebook written in Corso by a recent hire in our team, Jonathan

00:11:57.080 --> 00:11:58.400
Chang.

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:04.440
And as you can see, it uses BMS dash, and actually is not just BMS dash, but BMS dash

00:12:04.440 --> 00:12:12.039
for Corso, which my colleague Jimmy here made as an extension to BMS dash.

00:12:12.039 --> 00:12:17.239
And so yeah, just by kind of working through this, I think Jonathan put this together maybe

00:12:17.239 --> 00:12:18.840
in less than a week.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:24.880
He learned Corso, he learned connect, and kind of how to deploy all of this document.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:27.520
And by the way, he's a Python programmer.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:33.679
But we love Python at BMS too, and in this particular instance, he was trying to compare

00:12:33.679 --> 00:12:38.640
the speed in data wrangling in Pandas, Polars, and Modern.

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:48.599
So all that is to say, I think focusing on a small problem is really, really valuable.

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:52.679
The success of BMS dash, I think it's not the end of the story here.

00:12:52.679 --> 00:12:59.599
I like to think that it's the start of a culture of knowledge sharing in our team, and beyond

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:01.239
in the department as well.

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:07.919
So we have BMS dash, I eventually pull some of the theming out to a different package

00:13:07.919 --> 00:13:09.239
I call BMS pal.

00:13:09.239 --> 00:13:13.320
We have potent for those response analyses.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:18.559
So now scientists don't have to kind of copy code here and paste it there.

00:13:18.559 --> 00:13:23.799
We have all things BMS, which is actually not a package, but something I started writing

00:13:23.799 --> 00:13:28.000
down, you know, how to request access to this particular server.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.799
And then many other have contributed to it.

00:13:30.799 --> 00:13:35.960
So including my summer intern last year, so very excited about that.

00:13:35.960 --> 00:13:42.520
We also started BMS connect widgets, which is a package to track user stats on our deployed

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:43.520
documents.

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:44.520
Okay.

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:49.440
So my call to action for you today is that please be welcoming.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:53.840
If you have a new hire on your team now or soon, please invite them to contribute to

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:56.479
your existing project.

00:13:56.479 --> 00:14:00.559
Using the hashtag good first issue is a really good idea to do so, so they know where to

00:14:00.559 --> 00:14:01.559
look.

00:14:01.559 --> 00:14:04.000
Be kind and flexible and patient.

00:14:04.039 --> 00:14:05.039
You know, they're new.

00:14:05.039 --> 00:14:06.719
They still have a lot to learn.

00:14:06.719 --> 00:14:12.679
So don't make them contribute to something so big and expect results right away.

00:14:12.679 --> 00:14:17.599
If they contribute to your packages, give bravos, give authorships so that we can all

00:14:17.599 --> 00:14:20.760
build together.

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:21.760
And don't get me wrong.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:26.320
I think everyone on the slope will have to fall once in a while in order to learn.

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:30.479
But my hope is that together we can help each other fall a little bit more gracefully.

00:14:30.479 --> 00:14:31.479
Thank you.

00:14:31.479 --> 00:14:40.599
All right.

00:14:40.599 --> 00:14:41.880
Thank you, Cheng.

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:45.140
So again, we are taking questions on Slido.

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:50.359
So you've done a wonderful job of walking us through sort of that process.

00:14:50.359 --> 00:14:57.159
I'm wondering if you got to go back and do that again, what might you adjust or do differently?

00:14:57.159 --> 00:15:00.320
That's a great question.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:06.440
I think maybe just talking to more people and don't afraid of get networking, like Lydia

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:07.440
said.

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:12.039
Yeah, because it was, you know, when you started it, you feel like everything is so new and

00:15:12.039 --> 00:15:13.039
you don't know where things are.

00:15:13.039 --> 00:15:18.719
And so it took me a long time to kind of figure out all this information.

00:15:18.719 --> 00:15:21.559
But yeah, I think your co-workers are there to support you.

00:15:21.559 --> 00:15:23.559
So just get talking.

00:15:23.559 --> 00:15:24.559
Yeah.

00:15:24.559 --> 00:15:25.559
Fantastic.

